Dear Ms. Shaikjamaludeen,

I recently participated in a survey study of yours sent through Barrett's Honors Digest emails concerning self-efficacy and mathematical development, and I'd like to share with you a few comments on the nature of your study that could impact your data in a negative way.

Firstly, I'd caution you against making many assumptions about the personal lives of your participants when taking demographic information. For example, two of the questions ask for the highest educational attainment of the parents (mother and father respectively). This of course precludes those that grew up in single-parent households, orphans, or who perhaps grew up with same-sex parents. I would strongly suggest including a "Prefer Not To Answer" or "I Don't Know" answer for these types of questions to account for such cases, otherwise you'll get bogus data (if the participant doesn't quit the survey right there).

Secondly, for the mathematical portion of the study, I would refrain from calling it "mathematics". The questions involved are mostly just higher-level arithmetic. Also, it should be made extremely clear that such questions are to be answered without a calculator. Right now, there are no instructions, and my suspicion is that a majority of your respondents simply pulled up the calculator app on their device to do the questions, which makes the test trivial. You should mention that the arithmetic should be mental. You should also make very sure that the questions you have are actually correct; I recall seeing a question "x^2 + 14 = 36 - 22", for which the solution is clearly x = 0. However, the answer set included nonsense answers (2, 7, and 9 if I remember correctly), so I had no choice but to give a wrong answer.

I would hope that you will revise this survey keeping this advice in mind, as I can't imagine the data you currently have is worth very much as a result (particularly the calculator issue). I would also make a point of updating the English in many of the questions and answers to clarify any ambiguities that exist--remember that a crucial goal of writing is to have the reader understand it, not you.

Regards,

Rick Hewitt
